UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# TypeScript Introduction — Why Type Safety Matters\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nTypeScript is JavaScript with syntax for types. It is a superset of JavaScript — every valid JS file is valid TypeScript. But TypeScript adds static type checking that catches errors at compile time, before your code runs in production.\n\nAt companies like Microsoft (who created it), Google, Airbnb, and increasingly all major Indian tech companies, TypeScript is the standard for professional JavaScript development.\n\n> **Why it matters:** A `TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined` in production, discovered by a user at 2am, is a TypeScript error that would have been caught at coding time. TypeScript does not eliminate runtime errors completely, but it catches the most common class of bugs before they ship.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\n- Understand what TypeScript is and why it exists\n- Set up a TypeScript project\n- Understand the compilation process\n- Know the difference between static and dynamic typing\n- Write your first TypeScript code\n- Understand the TypeScript compiler (tsc)\n\n---\n\n## 3. TypeScript vs JavaScript\n\n```javascript\n// JAVASCRIPT — errors only discovered at runtime\nfunction getUser(id) {\n  return fetch(`/api/users/${id}`).then(r => r.json());\n}\n\nconst user = getUser(123);\nconsole.log(user.proflie.avatar); // Typo: "proflie" — crashes at runtime!\n\n// TYPESCRIPT — error caught immediately at coding time\ninterface User {\n  id:      number;\n  profile: { avatar: string; bio: string };\n}\n\nasync function getUser(id: number): Promise<User> {\n  const res = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);\n  return res.json();\n}\n\nconst user = await getUser(123);\nconsole.log(user.proflie.avatar);\n// ERROR at line 12: Property ''proflie'' does not exist on type ''User''.\n// Did you mean ''profile''?\n// ✅ Caught BEFORE shipping to production!\n```\n\n## 4. Setup & Compilation\n\n```bash\n# Install TypeScript\nnpm install -g typescript\nnpm install -D typescript ts-node\n\n# Check version\ntsc --version\n\n# Initialize tsconfig.json\ntsc --init\n\n# Compile a file\ntsc hello.ts          # Outputs hello.js\ntsc --watch           # Watch mode — recompile on save\ntsc --noEmit          # Type-check without outputting files\n\n# Run TypeScript directly (development)\nnpx ts-node hello.ts\n\n# Project with Vite (includes TypeScript)\nnpm create vite@latest my-app -- --template react-ts\n```\n\n## 5. tsconfig.json — Key Settings\n\n```json\n{\n  "compilerOptions": {\n    "target": "ES2020",          // Output JS version\n    "module": "ESNext",          // Module system\n    "lib": ["ES2020", "DOM"],     // Available APIs\n    "strict": true,              // Enable ALL strict checks\n    "noImplicitAny": true,       // Error on implicit any\n    "strictNullChecks": true,    // null/undefined must be explicit\n    "noUnusedLocals": true,      // Error on unused variables\n    "noUnusedParameters": true,  // Error on unused function params\n    "exactOptionalPropertyTypes": true,\n    "outDir": "./dist",          // Output directory\n    "rootDir": "./src",          // Source directory\n    "paths": {                   // Import aliases\n      "@/*": ["./src/*"]\n    },\n    "baseUrl": "."\n  },\n  "include": ["src"],\n  "exclude": ["node_modules", "dist"]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Type Checking in Practice\n\n```typescript\n// TypeScript catches these common bugs at compile time:\n\n// 1. Accessing property on possibly-null value\nconst user = getUser(); // might return null\nconsole.log(user.name); // Error: Object is possibly null\n// Fix: user?.name or if (user) { ... }\n\n// 2. Passing wrong argument type\nfunction double(n: number) { return n * 2; }\ndouble("5"); // Error: Argument of type ''string'' is not assignable to parameter of type ''number''\n\n// 3. Wrong return type\nfunction getCount(): number {\n  return "100"; // Error: Type ''string'' is not assignable to type ''number''\n}\n\n// 4. Accessing missing property\ninterface Config { debug: boolean; }\nconst cfg: Config = { debug: true };\ncfg.version; // Error: Property ''version'' does not exist on type ''Config''\n\n// 5. Typo in property name (real-world example)\nconsole.log(user.proflie); // Error: Did you mean ''profile''?\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is TypeScript and why would you use it over JavaScript?**\n> TypeScript is a statically typed superset of JavaScript developed by Microsoft. It adds optional type annotations, interfaces, generics, and other features that enable static analysis — the compiler finds type errors at build time. Use it because: (1) Catches bugs early, (2) Better IDE support (autocomplete, refactoring), (3) Self-documenting code, (4) Safer refactoring of large codebases.\n\n**Q: Does TypeScript replace JavaScript?**\n> TypeScript compiles TO JavaScript. Browsers and Node.js run JavaScript, not TypeScript. TypeScript is a development tool — it makes authoring easier and safer, but the output is always JavaScript. TypeScript types exist only at compile time and are completely erased from the output.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| TypeScript | JavaScript + static types |\n| Compile time | Errors caught before runtime |\n| Type erasure | Types removed in JS output |\n| `tsc` | TypeScript compiler |\n| `tsconfig.json` | Compiler configuration |\n| `strict: true` | Enable all strict type checks |\n\nTypeScript is not optional in professional development. It is the industry standard for JavaScript at scale. Learn it, use it, benefit from it.', 20, 1)
WHERE id = 'l40101';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Basic Types & Type Annotations — TypeScript Fundamentals\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nTypeScript''s type system is how you tell the compiler what kind of data a variable, function parameter, or return value should contain. Once you annotate, TypeScript enforces it everywhere that value is used.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Primitive Types\n\n```typescript\n// Explicit annotations\nlet name:    string  = "Alice";\nlet age:     number  = 25;\nlet isAdmin: boolean = false;\nlet score:   bigint  = 100n;\n\n// TypeScript usually INFERS the type — annotation is optional\nlet name    = "Alice";  // TypeScript infers string\nlet age     = 25;       // TypeScript infers number\nlet isAdmin = false;    // TypeScript infers boolean\n\n// Always annotate function parameters and return types\nfunction greet(name: string): string {\n  return `Hello, ${name}!`;\n}\n\n// Null and Undefined (with strictNullChecks)\nlet username: string | null      = null;       // Can be string or null\nlet description: string | undefined = undefined; // Can be string or undefined\nlet bio: string = null;                         // ERROR with strictNullChecks!\n\n// Special types\nlet anything:   any     = "could be anything"; // Opt-out of type checking (avoid!)\nlet unknown:    unknown = fetchData();          // Type-safe any — must narrow first\nlet never_used: never;                          // A value that never exists\nlet nothing:    void   = undefined;             // Function returns nothing\n```\n\n## 3. Arrays & Tuples\n\n```typescript\n// Array types\nconst titles:   string[]   = ["HTML5", "CSS3", "JavaScript"];\nconst scores:   number[]   = [95, 87, 92];\nconst mixed:    (string | number)[] = ["Alice", 25];\n\n// Alternative syntax\nconst titles2: Array<string> = ["HTML5", "CSS3"];\n\n// Readonly array\nconst LEVELS: readonly string[] = ["Beginner", "Intermediate", "Advanced"];\nLEVELS.push("Expert"); // ERROR — readonly!\n\n// Tuples — fixed length, fixed types at each position\nconst coordinate: [number, number] = [40.7128, -74.0060];\nconst entry:      [string, number] = ["Alice", 25];\nconst [name, score] = entry;  // Destructure with correct types\n\n// Named tuple members (TypeScript 4+)\ntype Point = [x: number, y: number, z?: number];\nconst pos: Point = [1, 2];        // z is optional\nconst pos3d: Point = [1, 2, 3];\n\n// Rest in tuples\ntype StringsAndNumber = [string, ...string[], number];\n```\n\n## 4. Object Types\n\n```typescript\n// Inline object type\nfunction createUser(user: { name: string; email: string; age?: number }) {\n  return user;\n}\n\n// Type alias\ntype User = {\n  id:         number;\n  name:       string;\n  email:      string;\n  department: string;\n  role:       "employee" | "mentor" | "admin"; // Literal union\n  xp?:        number;  // Optional property\n  readonly createdAt: Date; // Cannot be reassigned\n};\n\n// Index signature — object with dynamic keys\ntype Scores = { [courseId: string]: number };\nconst scores: Scores = { "html5": 95, "css3": 87 };\n\n// Intersection types — combine types\ntype WithTimestamps = { createdAt: Date; updatedAt: Date };\ntype CourseWithMeta = Course & WithTimestamps;\n```\n\n## 5. Union & Literal Types\n\n```typescript\n// Union types\ntype ID = string | number;\ntype Status = "active" | "inactive" | "pending";\ntype Result<T> = { success: true; data: T } | { success: false; error: string };\n\n// Literal types\ntype Direction = "north" | "south" | "east" | "west";\ntype Difficulty = "Beginner" | "Intermediate" | "Advanced";\ntype HttpMethod = "GET" | "POST" | "PUT" | "PATCH" | "DELETE";\n\n// Narrowing with union types\nfunction process(value: string | number): string {\n  if (typeof value === "string") {\n    return value.toUpperCase();  // TypeScript knows: string here\n  } else {\n    return value.toFixed(2);     // TypeScript knows: number here\n  }\n}\n\n// Template literal types\ntype EventName = `on${Capitalize<string>}`;\ntype RouteParam = `/:${string}`;\n```\n\n## 6. Type Narrowing\n\n```typescript\n// typeof\nfunction process(val: string | number | boolean) {\n  if (typeof val === "string")  { return val.toUpperCase(); }\n  if (typeof val === "number")  { return val * 2; }\n  if (typeof val === "boolean") { return !val; }\n}\n\n// instanceof\nfunction handleEvent(event: MouseEvent | KeyboardEvent) {\n  if (event instanceof MouseEvent)   { console.log(event.clientX); }\n  if (event instanceof KeyboardEvent) { console.log(event.key); }\n}\n\n// "in" operator\ntype Admin = { role: "admin"; permissions: string[] };\ntype User  = { role: "user"; courses: string[] };\n\nfunction handleUser(user: Admin | User) {\n  if ("permissions" in user) {\n    // TypeScript narrows to Admin\n    user.permissions.forEach(p => console.log(p));\n  }\n}\n\n// Type predicates\nfunction isString(val: unknown): val is string {\n  return typeof val === "string";\n}\n\nif (isString(value)) {\n  value.toUpperCase(); // TypeScript knows: string\n}\n\n// Discriminated unions\ntype Shape =\n  | { kind: "circle";    radius: number }\n  | { kind: "rectangle"; width: number; height: number }\n  | { kind: "triangle";  base: number; height: number };\n\nfunction area(shape: Shape): number {\n  switch (shape.kind) {\n    case "circle":    return Math.PI * shape.radius ** 2;\n    case "rectangle": return shape.width * shape.height;\n    case "triangle":  return 0.5 * shape.base * shape.height;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `any` and `unknown`?**\n> `any` completely disables type checking — you can do anything with an `any` value. `unknown` is the type-safe alternative — a value might be any type, but you must narrow it before using it. Use `unknown` for data from external sources (APIs, user input, JSON.parse); use `any` only as a last resort (it negates TypeScript''s benefits).\n\n**Q: What is a discriminated union?**\n> A discriminated union is a union type where each variant has a common property with a unique literal value (the discriminant). TypeScript uses this property to narrow the type in switch/if statements. Example: `{ kind: "circle" } | { kind: "square" }` — switching on `kind` narrows to the correct variant.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What is the difference between `string` and `String` in TypeScript?\n2. What does `string | null` mean?\n3. What is a tuple type?\n4. What is a literal type? Give an example.\n5. What is type narrowing?\n6. What is the difference between `any` and `unknown`?\n7. What does the `readonly` modifier do?\n8. What is a discriminated union?\n9. When does TypeScript infer a type automatically?\n10. What is the `never` type?\n\n---\n\n## 9. Lesson Summary\n\n| Type | Example |\n|------|--------|\n| Primitives | `string`, `number`, `boolean`, `null`, `undefined` |\n| Array | `string[]` or `Array<string>` |\n| Tuple | `[string, number]` |\n| Union | `string \\| number` |\n| Literal | `"admin" \\| "user"` |\n| Object | `{ name: string; age?: number }` |\n| `any` | Escape hatch — avoid |\n| `unknown` | Type-safe any — must narrow |\n| `never` | Unreachable type |\n\nType annotations are TypeScript''s primary tool. Annotate your function signatures, and TypeScript infers the rest. Use `strict: true`, avoid `any`, and let the type checker be your safety net.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l40201';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Interfaces & Type Aliases — Defining Contracts\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nInterfaces and type aliases are the two ways to name and reuse object types in TypeScript. They are the vocabulary of your application''s domain model — what a User looks like, what a Course contains, what an API response contains.\n\nWriting good interfaces is what makes a TypeScript codebase self-documenting and safe across team collaboration.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Interface vs Type Alias\n\n```typescript\n// TYPE ALIAS — can represent any type\ntype ID    = string | number;\ntype Point = { x: number; y: number };\ntype Callback<T> = (value: T) => void;\ntype Nullable<T> = T | null;\n\n// INTERFACE — specifically for object shapes, can be merged/extended\ninterface User {\n  id:   number;\n  name: string;\n  email: string;\n}\n\n// Key differences:\n// 1. Type aliases can represent primitives, unions, intersections\n// 2. Interfaces can be "merged" (declaration merging)\n// 3. Interfaces use extends; types use & intersection\n// 4. Performance: interfaces are slightly faster in large projects\n// General rule: prefer interface for objects, type for everything else\n```\n\n## 3. Complete Interface Syntax\n\n```typescript\ninterface Course {\n  // Required properties\n  id:          string;\n  title:       string;\n  description: string;\n  level:       "Beginner" | "Intermediate" | "Advanced";\n\n  // Optional properties\n  thumbnail?:     string;\n  estimatedHours?: number;\n\n  // Readonly — cannot reassign after creation\n  readonly createdAt: Date;\n  readonly authorId:  string;\n\n  // Method signatures\n  getModuleCount(): number;\n  enroll(userId: string): Promise<void>;\n\n  // Index signature — can have additional properties\n  [metaKey: string]: unknown;\n}\n\n// Extending interfaces\ninterface PublishedCourse extends Course {\n  publishedAt: Date;\n  viewCount:   number;\n  rating:      number;\n}\n\n// Extending multiple interfaces\ninterface AdminCourse extends PublishedCourse, Course {\n  adminNotes: string;\n  isHidden:   boolean;\n}\n\n// Implementing interface in a class\nclass CourseService implements Course {\n  id:          string;\n  title:       string;\n  description: string;\n  level:       "Beginner" | "Intermediate" | "Advanced";\n  readonly createdAt = new Date();\n  readonly authorId:  string;\n\n  constructor(data: Omit<Course, "createdAt" | "getModuleCount" | "enroll">) {\n    Object.assign(this, data);\n  }\n\n  getModuleCount() { return 0; }\n  async enroll(userId: string) { /* ... */ }\n}\n```\n\n## 4. Advanced Type Alias Patterns\n\n```typescript\n// Intersection types — combine multiple types\ntype Employee = User & {\n  department: string;\n  role:       "employee" | "mentor" | "admin";\n};\n\n// Conditional types\ntype NonNullable<T> = T extends null | undefined ? never : T;\ntype Flatten<T> = T extends Array<infer U> ? U : T;\n// Flatten<string[]> = string\n// Flatten<number> = number\n\n// Mapped types\ntype Readonly<T> = { readonly [K in keyof T]: T[K] };\ntype Partial<T>  = { [K in keyof T]?: T[K] };\ntype Required<T> = { [K in keyof T]-?: T[K] }; // Remove optionality\ntype Nullable<T> = { [K in keyof T]: T[K] | null };\n\n// Utility types (built-in TypeScript)\ntype UserPreview = Pick<User, "id" | "name" | "email">;    // Keep only these\ntype UserUpdate  = Partial<User>;                            // All optional\ntype NewUser     = Omit<User, "id" | "createdAt">;          // Remove these\ntype ReadonlyUser = Readonly<User>;                          // All readonly\ntype UserKeys    = keyof User;                               // "id" | "name" | ...\ntype UserValues  = User[keyof User];                         // Types of all values\n\n// Record type\ntype CourseIndex = Record<string, Course>; // { [id: string]: Course }\ntype Scores      = Record<"html5" | "css3" | "js", number>;\n\n// Template literal in types\ntype EventHandler<T extends string> = `on${Capitalize<T>}`;\n// EventHandler<"click"> = "onClick"\n```\n\n## 5. Real-World Interface Design\n\n```typescript\n// ====== API Response interfaces ======\ninterface ApiResponse<T> {\n  data:       T;\n  message:    string;\n  success:    boolean;\n  pagination?: {\n    page:       number;\n    perPage:    number;\n    total:      number;\n    totalPages: number;\n  };\n}\n\ninterface ApiError {\n  success: false;\n  error: {\n    code:    string;\n    message: string;\n    details?: Record<string, string[]>;\n  };\n}\n\n// Usage\ntype GetUsersResponse  = ApiResponse<User[]>;\ntype GetCourseResponse = ApiResponse<Course>;\n\n// ====== Form interfaces ======\ninterface LoginFormData {\n  email:      string;\n  password:   string;\n  rememberMe?: boolean;\n}\n\ninterface SignupFormData {\n  firstName:  string;\n  lastName:   string;\n  email:      string;\n  password:   string;\n  department: string;\n}\n\n// Form errors (Partial — not all fields may have errors)\ntype FormErrors<T> = Partial<Record<keyof T, string>>;\n// FormErrors<LoginFormData> = { email?: string; password?: string; rememberMe?: string; }\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: When should you use an interface vs a type alias?**\n> Use `interface` for object shapes that might be extended or implemented by classes. Use `type` for primitives, unions, intersections, and complex type computations. When in doubt, prefer `interface` for objects (better error messages, declaration merging) and `type` for everything else.\n\n**Q: What is declaration merging in TypeScript?**\n> Declaration merging means multiple `interface` declarations with the same name are automatically merged into one. This is useful for extending third-party library types without modifying source code. `type` aliases cannot be merged — redeclaring throws an error.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What is the difference between interface and type alias?\n2. How do you make a property optional in an interface?\n3. What does `readonly` do in an interface?\n4. How do you extend one interface from another?\n5. What is the `keyof` operator?\n6. What is a mapped type?\n7. What is `Pick<T, K>` used for?\n8. What is `Omit<T, K>` used for?\n9. What is declaration merging?\n10. What is an index signature?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Utility Type | Purpose |\n|-------------|--------|\n| `Partial<T>` | All properties optional |\n| `Required<T>` | All properties required |\n| `Readonly<T>` | All properties readonly |\n| `Pick<T, K>` | Keep only K properties |\n| `Omit<T, K>` | Remove K properties |\n| `Record<K, V>` | Object with keys K and values V |\n| `Nullable<T>` | T or null |\n| `keyof T` | Union of T''s property names |\n\nInterfaces and type aliases are the vocabulary of your application. Well-designed types act as documentation, catch mismatches early, and enable safe refactoring across large codebases.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l40301';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Generics — Writing Reusable, Type-Safe Code\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nGenerics are TypeScript''s most powerful feature for writing reusable code. Without generics, you would have to write a separate function for every type, or use `any` (which loses all type safety). With generics, you write the logic once and let TypeScript figure out the types.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Generic Functions\n\n```typescript\n// Without generics — duplicated code or type loss\nfunction firstString(arr: string[]): string  { return arr[0]; }\nfunction firstNumber(arr: number[]): number  { return arr[0]; }\nfunction firstAny(arr: any[]): any           { return arr[0]; } // No type safety!\n\n// With generics — ONE function, full type safety\nfunction first<T>(arr: T[]): T {\n  return arr[0];\n}\n\nfirst(["a", "b", "c"]);  // TypeScript infers: first<string> → returns string\nfirst([1, 2, 3]);         // TypeScript infers: first<number> → returns number\nfirst([{ id: 1 }]);      // TypeScript infers: first<{ id: number }>\n\n// Multiple type parameters\nfunction pair<A, B>(a: A, b: B): [A, B] {\n  return [a, b];\n}\npair("hello", 42);       // [string, number]\npair(true, { id: 1 });   // [boolean, { id: number }]\n\n// Explicit type arguments when inference fails\nconst result = first<User>(apiResponse);\n```\n\n## 3. Generic Constraints\n\n```typescript\n// Constrain T to have certain properties\nfunction getProperty<T, K extends keyof T>(obj: T, key: K): T[K] {\n  return obj[key];\n}\n\nconst user = { name: "Alice", age: 25, email: "alice@example.com" };\ngetProperty(user, "name");  // string\ngetProperty(user, "age");   // number\ngetProperty(user, "phone"); // ERROR: "phone" is not a key of user\n\n// Constrain with interface\ninterface HasId { id: string | number; }\n\nfunction findById<T extends HasId>(items: T[], id: string | number): T | undefined {\n  return items.find(item => item.id === id);\n}\n\n// Default type parameters\nfunction createState<T = string>(initial: T) {\n  let value = initial;\n  return {\n    get: () => value,\n    set: (v: T) => { value = v; },\n  };\n}\n\ncreateState<number>(0);    // Explicit\ncreateState("hello");      // Inferred as string\ncreateState();             // Uses default string type\n```\n\n## 4. Generic Classes & Interfaces\n\n```typescript\n// Generic class\nclass Repository<T extends { id: string }> {\n  private items: Map<string, T> = new Map();\n\n  save(item: T): void {\n    this.items.set(item.id, item);\n  }\n\n  findById(id: string): T | undefined {\n    return this.items.get(id);\n  }\n\n  findAll(): T[] {\n    return [...this.items.values()];\n  }\n\n  delete(id: string): boolean {\n    return this.items.delete(id);\n  }\n\n  find(predicate: (item: T) => boolean): T[] {\n    return this.findAll().filter(predicate);\n  }\n}\n\n// Usage — fully typed!\nconst userRepo   = new Repository<User>();\nconst courseRepo = new Repository<Course>();\n\nuserRepo.save({ id: "u1", name: "Alice", email: "alice@example.com" });\nuserRepo.findById("u1"); // Returns User | undefined — fully typed\n\n// Generic interface\ninterface ApiService<T> {\n  getById(id: string): Promise<T>;\n  getAll(): Promise<T[]>;\n  create(data: Omit<T, "id" | "createdAt">): Promise<T>;\n  update(id: string, data: Partial<T>): Promise<T>;\n  delete(id: string): Promise<void>;\n}\n\n// Implement for specific type\nclass UserService implements ApiService<User> {\n  async getById(id: string): Promise<User> {\n    const res = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);\n    return res.json();\n  }\n  // ... other methods\n}\n```\n\n## 5. Practical Generic Utilities\n\n```typescript\n// Result type — success or failure\ntype Result<T, E = Error> =\n  | { success: true;  data: T }\n  | { success: false; error: E };\n\nasync function safeCall<T>(fn: () => Promise<T>): Promise<Result<T>> {\n  try {\n    const data = await fn();\n    return { success: true, data };\n  } catch (error) {\n    return { success: false, error: error as Error };\n  }\n}\n\nconst result = await safeCall(() => fetchUser("123"));\nif (result.success) {\n  console.log(result.data.name); // Fully typed as User\n} else {\n  console.error(result.error.message);\n}\n\n// Pagination wrapper\ninterface PaginatedResult<T> {\n  items:      T[];\n  total:      number;\n  page:       number;\n  perPage:    number;\n  totalPages: number;\n}\n\nasync function getPaginated<T>(\n  fetch: (page: number, perPage: number) => Promise<{ items: T[]; total: number }>,\n  page: number = 1,\n  perPage: number = 20\n): Promise<PaginatedResult<T>> {\n  const { items, total } = await fetch(page, perPage);\n  return {\n    items,\n    total,\n    page,\n    perPage,\n    totalPages: Math.ceil(total / perPage),\n  };\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What are generics and why do you use them?**\n> Generics allow you to write code that works with multiple types while maintaining full type safety. Instead of writing the same function for strings, numbers, and objects separately (or using `any`), you write it once with a type parameter. TypeScript then infers or checks the correct types at each call site.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `T extends object` and `T extends {}`?**\n> `T extends {}` allows any non-null type (including primitives). `T extends object` restricts to actual object types (not primitives). Use `T extends Record<string, unknown>` for plain objects. Use `T extends object` when you need to exclude primitives.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does `<T>` mean in a generic function?\n2. How do you constrain a generic type?\n3. What is `keyof T`?\n4. What does `extends` mean in a generic constraint vs inheritance?\n5. How do you set a default type for a generic?\n6. When would you use multiple type parameters?\n7. What is `T[K]` called?\n8. How do generics relate to `any`?\n9. What is a conditional type?\n10. What does `infer` do in conditional types?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Pattern | Example | Use Case |\n|---------|---------|----------|\n| Generic function | `function f<T>(x: T): T` | Reusable with any type |\n| Constraint | `<T extends HasId>` | Require properties on T |\n| keyof | `<K extends keyof T>` | Safe property access |\n| Default | `<T = string>` | Default when not inferred |\n| Generic class | `class Repo<T>` | Type-safe data structures |\n| Conditional | `T extends U ? X : Y` | Type branching |\n\nGenerics are what make TypeScript''s type system Turing-complete. They are the difference between type stubs and a truly expressive type system that can model complex relationships in your application domain.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l40601';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# TypeScript with React — Professional Component Typing\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nTypeScript and React together are the industry standard for professional frontend development. When you add TypeScript to React, every prop, every state, every event handler becomes type-checked. Component misuse — wrong props, missing required data — becomes a compile error, not a runtime surprise.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Component Props Typing\n\n```typescript\nimport React, { ReactNode, FC } from "react";\n\n// Basic props interface\ninterface ButtonProps {\n  // Required props\n  label:    string;\n  onClick: () => void;\n\n  // Optional props\n  variant?:  "primary" | "secondary" | "ghost" | "danger";\n  size?:     "sm" | "md" | "lg";\n  disabled?: boolean;\n  loading?:  boolean;\n  type?:     "button" | "submit" | "reset";\n  className?: string;\n  children?:  ReactNode;\n  icon?:     ReactNode;\n}\n\n// Function component with explicit typing\nconst Button: FC<ButtonProps> = ({\n  label,\n  onClick,\n  variant = "primary",\n  size    = "md",\n  disabled = false,\n  loading  = false,\n  type     = "button",\n  className = "",\n  icon,\n}) => {\n  return (\n    <button\n      type={type}\n      onClick={onClick}\n      disabled={disabled || loading}\n      className={`btn btn-${variant} btn-${size} ${className}`}\n    >\n      {loading ? <span>Loading...</span> : icon}\n      {label}\n    </button>\n  );\n};\n\n// Usage — TypeScript checks all props\n<Button label="Enroll" onClick={handleEnroll} />;                // ✅\n<Button label="Submit" onClick={handleSubmit} variant="danger" />; // ✅\n<Button label="Go" />;                                           // ❌ Missing onClick\n<Button label="X" onClick={fn} variant="invalid" />;            // ❌ Wrong variant\n```\n\n## 3. Hooks Typing\n\n```typescript\nimport { useState, useEffect, useRef, useCallback, useMemo } from "react";\n\n// useState\nconst [count, setCount] = useState(0);          // Inferred: number\nconst [user, setUser]   = useState<User | null>(null); // Explicit generic\nconst [items, setItems] = useState<Course[]>([]); // Start empty, add later\n\n// useRef\nconst inputRef   = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null);\nconst timerRef   = useRef<number | null>(null);\nconst prevValue  = useRef<string>(""); // Mutable ref with initial value\n\n// Access with null check\nif (inputRef.current) {\n  inputRef.current.focus();\n}\n\n// useCallback\nconst handleSubmit = useCallback(\n  async (e: React.FormEvent<HTMLFormElement>) => {\n    e.preventDefault();\n    await submitForm(formData);\n  },\n  [formData] // TypeScript checks these deps\n);\n\n// useMemo\nconst filteredCourses = useMemo(\n  (): Course[] => courses.filter(c => c.level === selectedLevel),\n  [courses, selectedLevel]\n);\n\n// Custom hook with types\ninterface FetchState<T> {\n  data:    T | null;\n  loading: boolean;\n  error:   string | null;\n}\n\nfunction useFetch<T>(url: string): FetchState<T> {\n  const [state, setState] = useState<FetchState<T>>({\n    data: null, loading: true, error: null\n  });\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    let cancelled = false;\n\n    async function fetchData() {\n      try {\n        const res  = await fetch(url);\n        if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);\n        const data: T = await res.json();\n        if (!cancelled) setState({ data, loading: false, error: null });\n      } catch (err) {\n        if (!cancelled) setState({ data: null, loading: false, error: (err as Error).message });\n      }\n    }\n\n    fetchData();\n    return () => { cancelled = true; };\n  }, [url]);\n\n  return state;\n}\n\n// Usage with type parameter\nconst { data: courses, loading } = useFetch<Course[]>("/api/courses");\nconst { data: user }             = useFetch<User>(`/api/users/${id}`);\n// courses is Course[] | null — fully typed!\n```\n\n## 4. Event Handling Types\n\n```typescript\n// React provides typed event objects\nfunction handleClick(e: React.MouseEvent<HTMLButtonElement>) {\n  e.currentTarget;  // HTMLButtonElement — typed!\n  e.preventDefault();\n}\n\nfunction handleChange(e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) {\n  e.target.value;   // string\n}\n\nfunction handleSelectChange(e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLSelectElement>) {\n  e.target.value;   // string\n}\n\nfunction handleSubmit(e: React.FormEvent<HTMLFormElement>) {\n  e.preventDefault();\n  const formData = new FormData(e.currentTarget);\n}\n\nfunction handleKeyDown(e: React.KeyboardEvent<HTMLInputElement>) {\n  if (e.key === "Enter") { submit(); }\n  if (e.ctrlKey && e.key === "s") { save(); }\n}\n\nfunction handleDrop(e: React.DragEvent<HTMLDivElement>) {\n  const files = e.dataTransfer.files;\n}\n```\n\n## 5. Component Patterns\n\n```typescript\n// Children types\ninterface LayoutProps {\n  children: ReactNode;      // Any valid React content\n  header:   ReactElement;   // Must be a React element (not string/number)\n  sidebar?: ReactNode;      // Optional\n}\n\n// Polymorphic component (as prop pattern)\ntype ButtonAsProps<T extends React.ElementType> = {\n  as?: T;\n  children: ReactNode;\n} & React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<T>;\n\nfunction Button<T extends React.ElementType = "button">(\n  { as, children, ...rest }: ButtonAsProps<T>\n) {\n  const Tag = as ?? "button";\n  return <Tag {...rest}>{children}</Tag>;\n}\n\n<Button>Click</Button>             // Renders <button>\n<Button as="a" href="/courses">    // Renders <a href="/courses">\n<Button as={Link} to="/dashboard"> // Renders <Link to="/dashboard">\n\n// forwardRef\nconst Input = React.forwardRef<HTMLInputElement, InputProps>(\n  ({ label, error, ...props }, ref) => (\n    <div>\n      <label>{label}</label>\n      <input ref={ref} {...props} />\n      {error && <span className="error">{error}</span>}\n    </div>\n  )\n);\nInput.displayName = "Input";\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: How do you type the children prop in a React component?**\n> Use `ReactNode` for any valid React content (string, number, element, array, null). Use `ReactElement` if you specifically need a React element (not a string/number). Use `React.FC<Props>` shorthand (includes `children?: ReactNode` automatically in older versions — but explicit is better).\n\n**Q: How do you type a custom hook?**\n> Add explicit parameter types and return type annotation. Use generics to make hooks work with different data types. For hooks that return tuple-like values (like useState), type the return as a typed tuple: `[State, Dispatch<SetStateAction<State>>]`.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Lesson Summary\n\n| Pattern | Type |\n|---------|------|\n| Component props | `interface Props {}` |\n| Optional prop | `prop?: Type` |\n| Children | `children: ReactNode` |\n| useState | `useState<Type>(initial)` |\n| useRef (DOM) | `useRef<HTMLElement>(null)` |\n| Click handler | `React.MouseEvent<HTMLButtonElement>` |\n| Change handler | `React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>` |\n| Form handler | `React.FormEvent<HTMLFormElement>` |\n\nTypeScript with React eliminates an entire category of component bugs. Props are contracts — TypeScript enforces them at compile time so users of your component always get exactly what they need.', 30, 1)
WHERE id = 'l41101';
